result.execSummary:
The defendant Elizabeth J. Wilson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess w/Intent-Heroin (<=3g), a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1m)(d)1.
  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

[MK} case called at 10:03am. 
Defendant Elizabeth J. Wilson in court, in custody, with Attorney Robert Buckett.  ADA Jeffrey Shock appears for the State of Wisconsin.
Sentencing arguments are given by counsel.

On Count #1 the Court sentences Ms. Wilson to 4 1/2 years, with an Initial Term of Confinement in Prison of 18 months, and the maximum time to serve on Extended Supervision of 3 years.  This sentence is consecutive to any previously imposed sentence.

The Court finds that Ms. Wilson is eligible for the Earned Release Program.
The Court finds that Ms. Wilson is eligible for the Substance Abuse Program.
The Court gives 58 days credit for time already served.

The Court orders as conditions of Extended Supervision:
--to undergo AODA assessment and follow through with treatment recommendations
--to undergo any other assessment, treatment, counseling as required by the Agent
--to be subject to random drug  and alcohol screening
--no possession or consumption of illegal drugs
--no possession of drug paraphernalia
--no contact with any known drug offender except for treatment purposes as deemed appropriate by the Agent
--to comply with DNA sample provision upon demand
--to pay costs and surcharge including the $250 DNA surcharge 
--to pay $250 in drug testing fees


On Count #3 the Court sentences Ms. Wilson to serve 6 months in Jail (to be served in the WSPS) consecutive to Count #1.  
The Court orders entry of a civil judgment for the costs, fees, assessments and surcharges.
